hints_latex:
This is a Riemann sum. Recall that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle \Delta x = \frac{b-a}{n}
\end{align*}

and that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle x_{i} = a + i\Delta x.
\end{align*}

Then do a pattern match.

sols_latex:
From the question, we immediately see that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle \Delta x = \frac{1}{n}
\end{align*}

Now, to determine $\displaystyle x_{i}$, notice that we have that the
function is of the form

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle f(x_{i}) = \frac{1}{1 + (\tfrac{i}{n})^{2}}.
\end{align*}

The only composition of functions is underneath the square sign. So we
must have that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle f(x) = \frac{1}{1 + x^{2}}
\end{align*}

and hence that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle x_{i} = \frac{i}{n}
\end{align*}

As $\displaystyle x_{i} = a + i\Delta x$, we have that
$\displaystyle a = 0$ and hence since

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle \Delta x = \frac{1}{n} = \frac{b-a}{n} = \frac{b}{n}
\end{align*}

we have that $\displaystyle b = 1$. Combining the above gives

\begin{align*}
\lim_{n \to \infty}\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{1 + (\tfrac{i}{n})^{2}} = \int_{0}^{1}\frac{1}{1 + x^{2}}\,dx
\end{align*}

which completes the question.

statement_latex:
Express

\begin{align*}
\lim_{n \to \infty}\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{1 + (\tfrac{i}{n})^{2}}
\end{align*}

as a definite integral. \emph{Do not} evaluate the integral.
